    patterns_tag: "// The 5 trading patterns",
    patterns_title: "VolumeFilter isn't just color. It's decision.",
    patterns_lede: "The 5 patterns that show up on the chart every day and what to do in each. No fluff, no theory. Straight to the point.",
    pattern_when_label: "When to use",
    pattern_warn_label: "Caution",
    pattern_1_label: "BREAKOUT",
    pattern_1_h: "Breakout confirmation",
    pattern_1_p: "Every level breakout (resistance, support, IBH, IBL, PDH, PDL, range) needs at least one <strong style=\"color:var(--green)\">green</strong> bar on the break candle. Without that, it's false until proven otherwise. A candle that breaks gray or red = stops being hit, not institutional conviction.",
    pattern_1_when: "On every important level breakout. Don't trade the break without green confirmation.",
    pattern_1_warn: "Don't enter with a gray bar hoping \"the next one will confirm\". The signal needs volume ON the break candle.",
    pattern_2_label: "EXHAUSTION",
    pattern_2_h: "Trend exhaustion",
    pattern_2_p: "Every trend has a cycle: start (greens in a row), middle (gray mixed), end (predominantly red). The exhaustion signal is price continuing in the direction but volume turning <strong style=\"color:var(--red)\">red</strong> consistently, the classic price-volume divergence.",
    pattern_2_when: "In a winning trade, deciding whether to take profit or hold. Useful in rallies without pullback.",
    pattern_2_warn: "1–2 isolated reds is not exhaustion. Requires consistent pattern: 3+ in a row or 4 of the last 6.",
    pattern_3_label: "CLIMAX",
    pattern_3_h: "Climax volume",
    pattern_3_p: "A <strong style=\"color:var(--green)\">green</strong> bar absurdly above the average (3x, 4x+) after a long directional sequence <strong>often marks the turning point, not the start</strong>. Counter-intuitive: instinct says \"there's strength, it'll go far\", but it's the last buyer entering (up) or last seller capitulating (down).",
    pattern_3_when: "In stretched moves (5+ directional candles) and PDH/PDL tests. Take partial profit before reversal.",
    pattern_3_warn: "Climax is not a counter-trend entry by itself. The reverse trade needs more confirmation.",
    pattern_4_label: "ABSORPTION",
    pattern_4_h: "Institutional absorption",
    pattern_4_p: "The most subtle and valuable pattern: <strong style=\"color:var(--green)\">green</strong> bar on VolumeFilter but small candle in range (doji, pin bar, short body). Lots of volume traded, price standing still = someone large <strong>absorbing liquidity from the other side</strong>. Sign of strong reversal in the next candles.",
    pattern_4_when: "On important level tests when price gets stuck with long wicks and small bodies. R/R is usually 3:1 or better.",
    pattern_4_warn: "Don't confuse with low liquidity (gray/red + small candle = market sleeping). Absorption requires a GREEN bar.",
    pattern_5_label: "DISCIPLINE",
    pattern_5_h: "Dead day",
    pattern_5_p: "The hardest pattern: requires doing nothing. Last 30–60 bars overwhelmingly gray/red + greens that don't sustain = <strong style=\"color:var(--red)\">dead day</strong>. On that day, <strong>any trade gets stopped by noise</strong>. The trade you didn't take is a winning trade.",
    pattern_5_when: "Every morning before trading. Last 30 bars predominantly gray+red = low expectancy.",
    pattern_5_warn: "Don't force a trade to \"make up for\" yesterday. That thinking burns beginner accounts.",
